Document: Material
Path: godot/classes/class_material.rst
Summary: Describes the properties of the Material class in Godot Engine, specifically focusing on next_pass and render_priority.

Property: next_pass
Type: Material
Description: Sets the Material to be used for the next pass. This renders the object again using a different material.
Note: next_pass materials are not necessarily drawn immediately after the source Material. Draw order is determined by material properties, render_priority, and distance to camera.
Note: This only applies to StandardMaterial3D and ShaderMaterial with type "Spatial".
Methods:
- set_next_pass(value: Material) → void
- get_next_pass() → Material

Property: render_priority
Type: int
Description: Sets the render priority for objects in 3D scenes. Higher priority objects will be sorted in front of lower priority objects. In other words, all objects with render_priority 1 will render on top of all objects with render_priority 0.
Note: This only applies to StandardMaterial3D and ShaderMaterial with type "Spatial".
Note: This will not impact how transparent objects are sorted relative to opaque objects or how dynamic meshes will be sorted relative to other opaque meshes. This is because all transparent objects are drawn after all opaque objects and all dynamic opaque meshes are drawn before other opaque meshes.
Methods:
- set_render_priority(value: int) → void
- get_render_priority() → int
---CHUNK---
Document: Material
Path: godot/classes/class_material.rst
Summary: This section details private and public methods of the Material class in Godot Engine.

Method: _can_do_next_pass() -> bool
This method is virtual and const. It is only exposed for overriding and cannot be called directly. Internally, it determines whether the `next_pass` property should be visible in the editor.

Method: _can_use_render_priority() -> bool
This method is virtual and const. It is only exposed for overriding and cannot be called directly. Internally, it determines whether the `render_priority` property should be visible in the editor.

Method: _get_shader_mode() -> Shader.Mode
This method is virtual, required, and const. It is only exposed for overriding and cannot be called directly. It is used internally by various editor tools.

Method: _get_shader_rid() -> RID
This method is virtual, required, and const. It is only exposed for overriding and cannot be called directly. It is used internally by various editor tools to access the RID of the Material's Shader.

Method: create_placeholder() -> Resource
This method is const. It creates a placeholder version of this resource, specifically a PlaceholderMaterial.

Method: inspect_native_shader_code() -> void
This method is available only when running in the editor. It opens a popup window that visualizes the generated shader code, including all variants and internal shader code. This is similar to Shader.inspect_native_shader_code().